<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880224-0128 </DOCNO><HL> McDonnell Leads Defense Job Roster For Fiscal 1987 </HL><AUTHOR> Tim Carrington (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR><SO> </SO><CO> MD GD GE LK GM GMH RTN UTX BA GQ ML </CO><IN> ARO </IN><G> DEF </G><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   McDonnell Douglas Corp. climbed to first place on the Pentagon's latest roster of the 100 biggest military contractors.    The St. Louis-based builder of the F-18 Hornet, the F-15 fighter jet and the Apache helicopter received $7.7 billion in contracts in fiscal 1987, which ended last Sept. 30. That was up from $6.6 billion the previous year, when the company ranked third among defense contractors.    General Dynamics Corp. came in second with $7 billion in contracts, a drop from $8 billion in fiscal 1986, when it took first place. Among other systems, the contractor builds the F-16 fighter jet, the Trident submarine and the M-1 tank.    General Electric Co., the Pentagon's biggest engine maker, was the third-largest contractor in fiscal 1987 with $5.8 billion in contracts. The previous year, GE ranked second with $6.8 billion.    Lockheed Corp. placed fourth with $5.6 billion in contracts, up from $4.9 billion and a sixth-place ranking in fiscal 1986.    General Motors Corp., parent of Hughes Aircraft, placed fifth with $4.1 billion; in fiscal 1986, that company held the same ranking with $5.1 billion in contracts.    Raytheon Co. placed sixth with $3.8 billion in contracts; the previous year it ranked seventh with $4.1 billion.    Martin Marietta Corp. placed seventh in fiscal 1987 with $3.7 in defense jobs, up from a year-earlier ranking of 11th, when it had $2.9 billion.    United Technologies Corp. rose to eighth place with $3.6 billion in contracts, up from ninth place with $3.5 billion.    Boeing Co. dropped to ninth place, with $3.5 billion, from eighth place with $3.6 billion.    Grumman Corp. ranked 10th both years, with $3.4 billion in defense jobs in fiscal 1987, and $3 billion the previous year. </TEXT></DOC>